<span id="freeTextContainer13379126149288175148">The author provides a helpful “human” perspective to the social, political and economic implications/challenges of the necessary (inevitable?) transition to a coal-free (or more realistically, a far less-coal dependent) world. <br/><br/>The author argues correctly: (1) this transition from coal to clean/renewable energy is crucial if the global community is to arrest carbon build-up in the atmosphere; (2) the effort must be global; and (3) the role of government is central, as the private sector will not </span>
  <span id="freeText13379126149288175148" style="display:none">The author provides a helpful “human” perspective to the social, political and economic implications/challenges of the necessary (inevitable?) transition to a coal-free (or more realistically, a far less-coal dependent) world. <br /><br />The author argues correctly: (1) this transition from coal to clean/renewable energy is crucial if the global community is to arrest carbon build-up in the atmosphere; (2) the effort must be global; and (3) the role of government is central, as the private sector will not willingly abandon still profitable operations, nor provide sufficient aid to dislocated workers and their communities.<br /><br /></span>
